'''Cham''' is a [[municipalities of Switzerland|village]] in the [[Cantons of Switzerland|canton]] of [[Zug (canton)|Zug]] in [[Switzerland]].

==Location==
[[File:Lorze Cham.jpg|thumb|upright|left|The Lorze River flows through Cham]]
Cham has an area, {{as of|2006|lc=on}}, of {{km2 to mi2|17.8|abbr=on}}.  Of this area, 63.3% is used for agricultural purposes, while 13.2% is forested.  Of the rest of the land, 21.7% is settled (buildings or roads) and the remainder (1.8%) is non-productive (rivers, glaciers or mountains).<ref name=SFSO/>

Cham is located on the northern shore of [[Lake Zug]], {{km to mi|5.5|abbr=on}} to the north-west of the cantonal capital of [[Zug]].  Surrounding Cham, [[Steinhausen, Switzerland|Steinhausen]] is the east, [[H<U+00FC>nenberg]] is to the west, Lake Zug is south, and [[Knonau]] in the [[Canton of Z<U+00FC>rich]] is to the north.  The town has an area of {{km2 to mi2|19.82|abbr=on}}.  The train station is located {{m to ft|418|abbr=on}} above sea level and the highest point in town is {{m to ft|468|abbr=on}} above sea level.

The town is located at the mouth of the Lorze river, with two sections (Kirchb<U+00FC>hl and St<U+00E4>dtli) located on both sides of the river.  Cham also includes a number of smaller villages; Enikon, Lindencham, Friesencham, Hagendorn, Rumentikon, Niederwil, Oberwil and Bibersee.

==History==
[[File:Zugersee Cham.jpg|thumb|left|Lake Zug, near Cham]]
The shores of Lake Zug were populated at least 6000 years ago with several sites in Cham<ref name="HDS"/>.  A number of finds in the Oberwil village of Cham show that there were a number of middle and late [[Bronze Age Europe|Bronze Age]] settlements in Cham.  In 1944-45 a large, unique Roman [[watermill]] with multiple [[waterwheel]]s was found in Hagendorn village.  A Roman warehouse from the same era has been discovered in Heiligkreuz village.

The city's name, Cham, translates as village and refers to a large [[Celts|Celtic]] settlement on the shore of Lake Zug.  Following the collapse of the Western Roman Empire, there was also an [[Alamanni]]c settlement, but only placenames remain.  The first mention of the town (as ''Chama'') occurred on April 16, 858 when King [[Louis the German]] gave the town to his daughter, Hildegard, the abbess of the [[Fraum<U+00FC>nster]] Abbey in [[Z<U+00FC>rich]]<ref name="HDS"/>.  The town was administered by a variety of nobles and bailiffs over the following centuries.  

In 1360 the town was granted a [[charter]] as well as the rights to hold a market and enroll citizens<ref name="HDS"/>.  This charter, granted by [[Charles IV, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles IV]], was given to Gottfried von H<U+00FC>nenberg as the ruler of the city.  The [[House of Habsburg|Habsburgs]], attempting to maintain their influence in the region following the loss of Zug to the Swiss Confederation in 1364, bought part of the town in 1366 and completely bought the H<U+00FC>nenberg family out in 1370.  However, following the decisive Habsburg defeat in the [[Battle of Sempach]] in 1386, Cham was taken by Zug and Schwyz.  The Habsburgs had pawned the town to a citizen of Z<U+00FC>rich, G<U+00F6>tz M<U+00FC>lner, and so Zug was not able to completely own the city until the loan was repaid in 1415<ref name="HDS"/>.  The city would remain under the control of the [[vogt]] or bailiff of Zug until the [[Switzerland in the Napoleonic era|French invasion]] of 1798.

In the 16<sup>th</sup> Century the reform-minded preacher Jost M<U+00FC>ller unsuccessfully attempted to bring the [[Swiss Reformation|Reformation]] to Cham. 

Following the 1798 invasion of Switzerland the collapse of the [[Old Swiss Confederacy]], Cham finally became an independent town.  Though the citizens still paid some taxes and tithes to Zug until 1816 when most were abolished and 1872 when the last one ended. 

The rapid industralization of the second half of the 19<sup>th</sup> Century caused a population boom in Cham and the surrounding villages.  The population doubled between 1850 and 1880 and continued to grow at a slightly slower rate afterward.  The first urban plan and construction ordinances came into being in 1950.  A goal of the planning was to maintain the character of the industrial part of the city, becomes a center for the surrounding villages and preserve the parkland along the lake.  In 1991 the town was awarded the [[Wakker Prize]] for the preservation of its architectural heritage.  By 1990 Cham was the third largest city in the Canton of Zug.

==Demographics==
Cham has a population (as of {{Swiss populations date|CH-ZG}}) of {{Swiss populations|CH-ZG|1702}}.{{Swiss populations ref|CH-ZG}}  {{As of|2008|December}} 19.6% of the population was made up of foreign nationals.  Over the last 10 years the population has grown at a rate of 14%.  Most of the population ({{as of|2000|lc=on}}) speaks German (85.7%), with Serbo-Croatian being second most common ( 3.1%) and Italian being third ( 1.9%).<ref name=SFSO>[http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/en/index/regionen/regionalportraets/gemeindesuche.html Swiss Federal Statistical Office] accessed 22-Sep-2009</ref>

In the 2007 [[Swiss federal election, 2007|federal election]] the most popular party was the [[Swiss People's Party|SVP]] which received 31.3% of the vote.  The next three most popular parties were the [[Christian Democratic People's Party of Switzerland|CVP]] (22.2%), the [[Free Democratic Party of Switzerland|FDP]] (18.2%) and the [[Green Party of Switzerland|Green Party]] (17.8%).<ref name=SFSO/>

The entire Swiss population is generally well educated.  In Cham about 76.4% of the population (between age 25-64) have completed either non-mandatory [[Education in Switzerland#Secondary|upper secondary education]] or additional higher education (either University or a ''[[Fachhochschule]]'').<ref name=SFSO/>

The historical population was<ref name="HDS">{{HDS|788|Cham}}</ref><ref name="BfS">{{cite web| last = Bundesamt fur Statistik (Federal Department of Statistics)| title = Bilanz der st<U+00E4>ndigen Wohnbev<U+00F6>lkerung (Total) nach Bezirken und Gemeinden| year = 2008| url = http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/de/index/themen/01/02/blank/key/raeumliche_verteilung/kantone__gemeinden.html| format = Microsoft Excel| accessdate = November 5, 2008}}</ref> 
