==Weather==
Cham has an average of 136.1 days of rain per year and on average receives {{mm to in|1147|abbr=yes}} of [[Precipitation (meteorology)|precipitation]].  The wettest month is June during which time Cham receives an average of {{mm to in|144|abbr=yes}} of precipitation.  During this month there is precipitation for an average of 13.5 days.   The driest month of the year is February with an average of {{mm to in|69|abbr=yes}} of precipitation over 13.5 days.<ref name=MeteoSchweiz>{{cite web| url =http://www.meteoswiss.admin.ch/web/de/klima/klima_schweiz/tabellen.html | title =Temperature and Precipitation Average Values-Table, 1961-1990   | accessdate= 8 May 2009| publisher =Federal Office of Meteorology and Climatology - MeteoSwiss | language = German, French, Italian}}, the weather station elevation is 440 meters above sea level.</ref>

==Sights and Recreation==
This small town has its own medical clinic, excellent institutions for primary and secondary education, kindergarten and an excellent public green with sports facilities available all year around.

Cham also provides visitors and residents alike with hotel services, congress hall, churches (catholic & reformist), a marina, and a castle ([[Schloss St. Andreas|St. Andreas]]).  The church of St. James is a late [[Baroque architecture|Baroque]] building from the 18<sup>th</sup> Century, with a late [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] tower from the 15<sup>th</sup> Century<ref>[http://www.cham.ch/de/portrait/sehenswuerdigkeiten/welcome.php?action=showobject&object_id=306 City of Cham-Church of St. James] accessed 31 December 2008. {{de_icon}}</ref>.  There are several well established restaurants providing a variety of local and international cuisines.

===Heritage sites of national significance===
There are a number of Swiss [[Swiss inventory of cultural property of national and regional significance|heritage sites of national significance]] in Cham.  These include the ''Eslen'', a [[Neolithic]] lake shore settlement, the church and [[Cistercian]] [[convent]] at Frauenthal, the Castle of St. Andreas, two buildings in the old city, and the brickyard.<ref>[http://www.bevoelkerungsschutz.admin.ch/internet/bs/de/home/themen/kgs/kgs_inventar.html Swiss inventory of cultural property of national and regional significance] 21.11.2008 version, {{de icon}} accessed 22-Sep-2009</ref>

==Transportation==
Cham is located {{km to mi|5.5|abbr=on}} from Zug and is centrally located between [[Luzern]] ({{km to mi|25|abbr=on}}) and [[Z<U+00FC>rich]] ({{km to mi|32|abbr=on}}).  The [[SBB-CFF-FFS]] train line from Luzern through [[Thalwil]] to Z<U+00FC>rich stops in Cham.  The [[European route E41|E41]] highway passes near Cham.  The city can also be reached by bus from Zug and in the summer by boat.

==Industry==
Cham has an unemployment rate of 2.05%.  {{as of|2005}}, there were 206 people employed in the [[Primary sector of the economy|primary economic sector]] and about 68 businesses involved in this sector.  2,151 people are employed in the [[Secondary sector of the economy|secondary sector]] and there are 179 businesses in this sector.  4,900 people are employed in the [[Tertiary sector of the economy|tertiary sector]], with 783 businesses in this sector.<ref name=SFSO/>

For most of Cham's history, farming and light industry were the main sources of income.  The Lorze River has always been a key for the development of the city.  The first recorded watermill in Cham was built in 1279.  About 1641 a [[dyeing]] and bleaching operation was built along the river.  In 1657 a paper mill was built, which partly mechanized in the 1720s and had the first paper machine in 1840.  Following several mergers and expansions, this factory became the first Swiss [[wood pulp]] factory.  In the 20<sup>th</sup> Century it became ''Papierfabrik Cham AG'' the largest company in Cham.  

In 1863 a [[cotton]] spinning and weaving company opened in Cham.  Following a major fire in 1888 the factory closed, but the [[Dormitory|dormitories]] for child laborers for the factory are now a children's home.

In 1864 Cham was connected to the Z<U+00FC>rich-Lucerne train line.  In 1866 the American Page family founded the Anglo-Swiss Condensed Milk Co. in Cham to take advantage of this new rail line.  The company initially produced only condensed milk, but soon grew to produce other milk products.  In 1905 it merged with the [[Farine Lact<U+00E9>e Henri Nestl<U+00E9> Company]] to form [[Nestl<U+00E9>]].  The company expanded rapidly and by 1907 they had over 1000 [[milkmen]] in 44 locations.  In 1913 a conflict over money between the factory and the milkmen led to a strike and weakened the company.  Following World War I, the company faced financial crisis and began to shut down production in Cham.

In 1905 one-third of the population worked in agriculture, while half worked in industry.  By 1955 nearly two-thirds of the population worked in industry.  In the following year industrial jobs decreased while the central location and low taxes encouraged a growth in service industries.  In 2001 80% of the businesses and 58% of the jobs are in service industries, while 40% are in manufacturing<ref name="HDS"/>.

==People==
*[[Victor Villiger]] (1868<U+2013>1934), chemist, was born in Cham.
